The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
Archives
 Corporate Briefs
																								 Tata Metaliks has clocked an 85 per cent increase in profit after tax at Rs 28.21 crore for the half-year ended September 2007 compared with Rs 15.24 crore in the first half of 2006-07. The company registered a 38.46 per cent rise in turnover at Rs 449.73 crore during the period against Rs 324.82 crore in the corresponding period a year ago.																								 Advinus Therapeutics and Drugs for Neglected Diseases Initiative, a Geneva-based non-profit organisation, has formed a collaboration for discovery and development of novel therapies for visceral leishmaniasis.																								 Bank of India has announced a term deposit scheme for exchange earners foreign currency (EEFC) account holders. Under the scheme, the EEFC term deposits will be accepted for various fixed periods.																								 Aptech has launched its brand N-Power. It will also open 50 centres in the country by December 2007. N-Power will address the training requirements for certified hardware and software networking programmes.																								 Schneider Electric has opened a plant in Hyderabad. This is the companys ninth global plant in the country. Schneider Electric makes products such as circuit breakers, contractors, push buttons and pilot lamps. 																								 Tata Chemicals has won the ICC Aditya Birla Award for Best Responsible Care Committed Company and the ICC Award for Social Responsibility. The awards were announced by the Indian Chemicals Council, Mumbai.																								 Shree Cement has despatched 4.72 lakh tonnes in September this year, a 21.03 per cent rise from 3.9 lakh tonnes a year ago. The company despatched 28.37 million tonnes between April and September.																								 General Mills has launched Nature Valley Granola Bars in the city. The bars are made of wholegrain oats, fruits and nuts. A single-bar costs Rs 12, a double pack Rs 20 and a pack of six double bars Rs 120.																								 HCL Infosystems has unified its various environment protection initiatives under its HCL eSafe programme. The company has also launched a line-up of desktop computers compliant with the restriction of hazardous substances directive. 																								 ProCurve Networking, a business unit of HP has implemented sFlow Technology for wireless network access. ProCurve and InMon Corporation jointly developed the wireless extensions for sFlow. ADVERTISEMENT
